│ peeling inside peelLoop when attempting to replace uses of original exit      │
│ values with the corresponding values from the peeled iteration. The code      │
│ dereferences a WeakTrackingVH from VMap using '&*VMap.lookup(E)'. This        │
│ assumes the mapped value exists and hasn't been deleted. In this reproducer,  │
│ the mapped value has been deleted (e.g., due to constant folding/remapping),  │
│ making the WeakTrackingVH empty and leading to the assertion 'Dereferencing   │
│ deleted ValueHandle'.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe logs show that          │
│ loop-unroll decides to peel 1 iteration (\"Peel 0 iteration(s) to turn some   │
│ Phis into invariants.\" then \"PEELING loop %loop with iteration count 1!\"). │
│ The crash happens immediately after entering peelLoop. The failure backtrace  │
│ points to the line where replaceAllUsesWith is called with                    │
│ '&*VMap.lookup(E)'. Given the trivial instructions in the loop body (select   │
│ 0,0; sub 0,0; xor 0,0), it's likely that during cloning/remapping these       │
│ become constants and the cloned instructions may be replaced and possibly     │
│ erased, invalidating the WeakTrackingVH.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe      │
│ peelLoop implementation assumes that every exit value E has a valid           │
│ corresponding cloned value in VMap at the time of RAUW, and dereferences the  │
│ WeakTrackingVH without checking. However, remapInstructionsInBlocks and       │
│ subsequent adjustments can result in the cloned value being RAUW'ed to        │
│ constants and potentially erased, which clears the WeakTrackingVH.            │
│ Dereferencing it triggers the assertion. Therefore, the root cause is unsafe  │
│ dereferencing of a WeakTrackingVH that may be null due to earlier             │
│ transformations.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit in                       │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp at the block handling ExitValues when  │
│ PeelLast is true. Replace the direct dereference '&*VMap.lookup(E)' with a    │
│ safe fallback: if the mapped value exists, use it; otherwise, use E (or the   │
│ constant if E is constant). This maintains correctness in common cases and    │
│ avoids dereferencing a deleted value handle.\n\nProposed change (lines        │
│ 1259-1262):\n- Current:\n  P->replaceAllUsesWith(isa<Constant>(E) ? E :       │
│ &*VMap.lookup(E));\n- Replace with:\n  {\n    Value *Mapped = nullptr;\n      │
│ if (!isa<Constant>(E)) {\n      auto VH = VMap.lookup(E);\n      Mapped = VH  │
│ ? VH.getValue() : nullptr;\n    }\n    Value *NewV = isa<Constant>(E) ? E :   │
│ (Mapped ? Mapped : E);\n    P->replaceAllUsesWith(NewV);\n  }\nThis checks    │
│ the WeakTrackingVH before dereferencing. If it is empty, it falls back to the │
│ original value E, which remains valid. If E is a constant, it uses E directly │
│ as before.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy guarding against null WeakTrackingVH and     │
│ avoiding unsafe dereferencing, we prevent the assertion crash in peelLoop     │
│ when peeling the last iteration in cases where cloned exit values have been   │
│ deleted due to remapping/constant folding. This change stabilizes loop        │
│ peeling for trivially computable loop bodies like the reproducer while        │
│ keeping the intended behavior in the common case where the mapped value       │
│ exists."                                                                      │
